Spotify Streaming in Germany Before and During the First Wave of the COVID-19 Pandemic:

Compared and Predicted

Kework K. Kalustian, M.A.

Music Dept., Max Planck Institute for Empirical Aesthetics, Frankfurt/Main, Germany

kework.kalustian@ae.mpg.de

BACKGROUND

  • The COVID-19 pandemic is an event with far-reaching consequences.
  • Several negative consequences are observable.
  • Yet, people tend to use more musical media during nationwide lockdowns (Fink et al., 2021).

AIMS

\(RQ\): To what extent was music more streamed during the so-called first wave of the COVID-19 pandemic (March 11, 2020, until June 29, 2020) compared with the same period before the pandemic, and how is daily music listening predictable during the COVID-19 pandemic?

HYPOTHESES

  • H1: People tend to stream more of Germany’s daily top 200 Spotify charts during the COVID-19 pandemic than in a comparable reference period (\(r ≥ .10\)).
  • H2: The stream counts of Germany’s daily top 200 Spotify charts during the COVID-19 pandemic are predictable based on daily stream counts from January 01, 2019, to March 10, 2020 (\(MAPE ≤ 5\)).

METHODS

DATA RETRIEVAL & CLEANING

  • Web-scraping: Germany’s daily top 200 chart positions, song titles, their stream counts, and track IDs between January 01, 2019, and June 29, 2020 (\(N = 109200\)) from Spotify’s website (\(546\) days \(*\) \(200\) chart positions).
  • How?
  • By using arguments of Hadley Wickham’s R package rvest for scraping websites within a simple function and by using his tidyverse):

DIFFERENCE TEST

Median summarized stream counts per day of the “pre-pandemic period” (March 11, to June 29, 2019; \(n_{Pre-Pandemic} = 111\)) and the “pandemic period” (March 11, to June 29, 2020; \(n_{Pandemic} = 111\)) compared:

  • How?

  • Via One-way paired Wilcoxon test (according to H1)

Figure 2
Connected Scatter plot: Daily Stream Counts of Germany’s Daily top 200 Spotify Charts per Period.
Note. \(p < .001\), \(z = -3.61\), \(r = .343\), \(CL = 95\)%, \(n = 111\)
  • People streamed more during the pandemic (moderate effect).
